{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600672/1930060701/0352.xml":{"full_text":".p\n16th ST. HEIGHTS\nToo late for picture\u2014\nCome out to\n1415 Holly St. N.W.\nand see a real home. f\nW. C. KREMKAN\nGeorgia 3812\n\n522\nINGRAHAM\nST. N.'W.\nOn one of the most at\ntractive streets in Pet-\nworth I\u2014a 1 \u2014a Dunigan-built\nhome of six \"rooms, ga\nrage and two screened\nporches. The lot is more\nthan 150 feet deep, mak\nj ing an unusually large\nback yard. Jt is well\nlandscaped and streets,\nand alleys are all paved.\nExceptionally conven\nient\u2014being within two\nblocks of the bus, both\ncar lines and stores.\nOpen for Inspection\nEvery Day Until 9 P.M.\ni i\nD. J. Dunigan, Inc.\nTower Bldg. Nat 1 126) j\nl\nI\nJ\nSPEAKING\nOF VALUES!\nSee This\nModem\nAll-Brick\nHome\nToday\n2923 7th St. N.E.\nBROOKLAND\nt V yt.\nI\nOnly\n#7,450\nSSOO CASH\nTerms Like Rent\n\u2014These Features\u2014\n-8 Rooms and Rath\nIll'S\nSteeping: Torch\nBreakfast Porch\nButtt-in Garage\nLarge Lot\n\nOpen All Day Sunday\nAn out.-t aniline value in a modern\nall-brick home in progressive Brook\nland Beautifully decorated and\nfinished throughout. Hot-water heat,\nnew awnings installed by Woodward\nLothrop. inlaid linoleum on kitchen\nfloor. Plenty of floor plugs Barge\nlandscaped lot on paved street and\nalley. Two bus lines pass door.\nTODAY\u25a0 Drier nut Rhode Island\nAve. to 4th St. N.E., turn north on\n4th to Franklin St., then east to 7th\nand the properly. Or take bus at\ni 10th and K Sts. N.W. marked Hv\nattsville or I.aurel and vet off at\n7th end Girard, tits. S.E.. in front\nof property. Or take street car\nmarked Bronkland at 15th and G\nSts. N.W.. art off at 7th and Monroe\nSts. N.F... and ualk south on 7th to\nFranklin.\nSee Mr. Morgan\nM. 8C R. B. Warren\n8950 Conn. Cleveland\nAve. 7.180\nREAL ESTATE.\nCHICAGO DOCTOR\u2019S\nj AFFAIRS TANGLED\nRescued From Kidnapers,\nI Demanding Ransom, and\nHeld on Criminal Charge.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, June 7.\u2014Several things\nhappened in the life of Dr. Frank L.\nNathanson between 3 p.m. yesterday\nand dawn of today.\nHe was kidnaped from his office at\nj the point of a pistol, threatened with i\nj death, held prisoner for ransom, was\n1 rescued by detectives and finally was\ni himself locked up on a criminal charge. 1\nDetectives, notified by the physician's\n'secretary that he was a captive, res\ncued him from the home of Mrs. Car\nmello Lupreto. They arrested Mrs.\nLupreto and August Husateri.\nAt the police station Dr. Nathanson\nwas ordered held when the woman\nsigned a complaint charging him with i\nhaving performed an illegal operation\nupon her 16-year-old daughter, Anna.\nDr. Nathanson signed a complaint j\ncharging Mrs. Lupreto and Pusateri\nwith kidnaping and extortion. The j\ngirl, Anna, was sent to the Juvenile\nHome. And to round out.the cycle .of\nallegations. George Robertson, described\nas the girl\u2019s sweetheart, was held on\ncharges of contributing to the delin\nquency of a minor.\nDr. Nathanson was in his office yes-\nterday afternoon when Mrs. Lupreto\nentered, demanding that he accompany j\nher at once to her home, saying her\ndaughter was dying. When he delayed,\nthe woman produced a pistol, he said, j\nand threatened to kill him.\nAt the Lupreto home, according to\nthe physician\u2019s story, the demand for\nj money was made. At 6 p.m. Dr. Na- j\nthanson telephoned his secretary to\nj bring some blank checks. \u201cI must pay I\nI out SIO,OOO right away,\u201d he said,\ni hoping by this to inform his secretary\nj that he was being held against his will.\nThe secretary notified police. When I\nthe police reached the Lupreto home j\nthey found Dr. Nathanson had signed a j\ncheck for S2OO and a note promising\nj SBOO more in installments.\nOn two previous occasions Dr. Na\nthanson has had experience with gun\nattacks. In July, 1921, he shot and j\nkilled in his office two men who, he\nsaid, had tried to rob him. In Novem-\nI ber, 1925, he fired six shots at two gun-\nmen who called at the office to avenge\ni some grievance which the doctor de\nclined to discurs.\nAPARTMENT DWELLINGS\nPERCENTAGE FALLS OFF\nAccording to building permit reports\nreceived by the Bureau of Labor Sts\ntistics from 257 identical cities having j\na population of 25,000 or over, there was I\na slight decrease in the percentage of\nhomes provided in new apartment\nhouses in 1929 as compared with 1928.\nIn 1929 family accommodations were\nprovided in all classes of dewllings in\nthese 257 cities for 244,197 families,\nwhile in 1928 provision was made for\n388,678 families. According to permits\nissued in these cities during 1929, 48 6\nper cent of ths families were to be\nhoused in apartment houses and 40.2\nper cent in one-family dwellings. In\n1928 53.7 per cent were provided for in\napartment houses and only 35.2 per\ncent in one-family dwellings.\nDuring each of the last four years more\nfamilies have been provided for in\napartment houses than in one-family j\ndwellings in these cities. This change\nin the type of building is causing some\nchange in the building trades employed, 1\nwith a larger proportion of structural\niron workers and bricklayers.\nGavel Made of Bits,\nFrom Hoover Office\nGiven to Builders\nA gavel, fashioned from pieces\nof wood that once formed part\nof the trim ol the executive of\nfice of the President, which was\nturned to shambles by the fire\nlast Christmas eve. has been\npresented to the Building Trades\nEmployers\u2019 Association of Wash\nington.\nThe gift came from WilliamT.\nBlunt, 118 Carroll street sout,)*-\neast, a member of the local Car\npenters\u2019 Union, who was em\nployed by the C. H. Tompkins\nCo. in the rehabilitation of the\nworkshop of President Hoover.\nIn a letter to the association\naccompanying the gift Mr. Blunt\nstates that the gavel is a com\nposition of pieces of the oak hand\nrail once used on the stairs of\u2014\nthe main floor of the executive\noffice, a piece of the mahogany\nborder of the floor of the Presi\ndent's private office, two pieces\nof the black walnut squares used\nin the cabinet room floor and\npieces of mahogany from the\nPresident's office.\nni rrini-===iniimr= \u25a0-\u25a0\u25a0ini inn in\n0 9th and DAHLIA STS., N. W. 11\nWILL CONSIDER YOUR OLD HOME IN\n0 EXCHANGE AS PART PAYMENT\nIf] s rooms nFTAPHFn\n2 BATfIS 1/L' 1 JtWsK&nJllJ Enjoy tlic advan-\nU 2-CAR \u00bbR,CK BRICK XZSSiZ i'\nGARAGES m homes, at prices that\nOPEN FIREPLACE O V/IVILiIS arc less thatl you\nELECTRIC RE- nm/IFT\\ woukl pay or row\nfr II M\u25a0 1 houses of their size.\nu FRIGERATION t X\\l\\,EtU\nCOI ONI \\T From* This Well-landscapcd Lot\nis 45x104 Feet\nFRONT F $10,500 EXCELLENT\nNORTHWEST f\n,RUIKS to RESIDENTIAL L\n0 MANY ADDED G* \u201ct A AC A \u00abSECTION\nfeatures if) irr\u00ae%/OU\n\nOPEN DAILY to 9:01) P.M. M:\ny 7012 9th STREET N.W. F\n(One Block East of Ga. Ave., at Dahlia St.)\nCOME OUT TODAY AND SEE WHAT WE ARE OFFERING\nn WAPLE JAMES, Inc. fj\n1226 14th Street N.W. North 0962 [J\nI r\" ini =ini :Mni irii <E\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON. T>. C.. SATI KOAV. -U NE 7. Wit).\nMODERN STRUCTURE OFFERS\nCONTRAST AT ALEXANDRIA\n1111 1 inn 4 i\nI The active construction program in\n1 Alexandria has produced a striking\nj contrast between the new and the old.\nAlmost surroundccUby historic Colo\nnial homes in the ffcart of the town,\nthe new building of the Virginia Public\nj Service Co., ultra-modern in plan,\ntreatment and equipment, was recently\ncompleted.\nThe building, located at .the north\n-1 west corner of Prince and Washington\nj streets, is of restrained modernistic style,\ni faced with limestone. Ornamental iron\nFOR YOU CITY PEOPLE II\nI who want real seaside life, with that rare combination of Kg\nj pine groves, real shade trees, picturesque lakes, real salt mmt\nwater bathing in the old Chesapeake Bay itself. Best, W\nsafest, cleanest sand beach for the kiddies to romp, swim lu\ni and play. Pine fishing, boating, tennis, land and water K'S\nsports. In short; an ideal place in an established colony wfl\nof individually owned and occupied private dwellings. VI\nHere .is just the kind of a homesite with all improvements, W\u00ae\n1 which you have been looking for. IZ\nj Arrange for your Summer home now\u2014at \u00a9FI\nI BAY RIDGE REALTY GORP. If\nPeter .1. Hagan, Local Representative\n219 Bond Bldg. Nat. 9657\njSSSSSSSSSSS&SSSS2SSSSSSSSRSSSSSS3SSSSSSBEESS&SS3SSSSSSSSg j\nOne of the Best Buys in N.E.\nPriced Under SB,OOO\nInspect at Once\n1601 to 1619 D St. N.E.\njr~ The architecture of these\nfine homes has been care\nde.ifined and .elected\n\nsilPllt laff\u00ae These homes contain six,\ni even and ei ht lar e\nv: rooms, tile hath and built\n\u25a0\u2014l\u2014 1 in end ehnwer, one-\nTHOS. A. JAMESON CO.\n906 New York Ave. National 5526\n\"Ask the Man ICho Owns One\"\nwork has been generously employed at\nthe entrances, window frames and other I\nexterior decoration.\nAn unusual feature of the exterior is 1\ni a central panel of decorative glass,!\nj which is illuminated at night, throw- i\ning the face of the building into strong j\nl relief.\nThe interior as well as the exterior is j\n1 modernistic in design,\nj The -interior is trimmed with walnut.;\nI Walls are of a salmon tint, relieved by\nI fluted silver stripes in the first story.\nSECURITIES SAFETY\nWILL BE DISCUSSED\nRealtor Convention in Toronto to\nConsider Means of\nProtection.\nProtecting the safety of securities\u2014-a\nthought which ever since the stock\nmarket slump has been uppermost in\nthe minds of all investing folk, from\nthe purchaser of a SIOO unit to the\ncompany which handles investment\nfunds on a gigantic scale\u2014will be dis\ncussed before the members of the mort\ngage and finance division of the Na\ntional Association of Real Estate Boards\nat its twenty-third annual convention,\nto be held In Toronto, Canada, July 9,\n10 and 11.\n\u201cHow to Safeguard Real Estate Se\ncurities Through Proper Planning and\nEfficient Management\u201d will be discussed\nby Walter S. Schmidt, Cincinnati, in his\naddress before the mortgage brokers.\nAn Attractive Home In Beautiful Edgemoor\nA REAL VALUE!\nA home of distinctive individuality!\ng Designed along strikingly beautiful lines\nwith eight large rooms and two baths,\nconsisting of a large living room, din\ning room, breakfast room and kitchen\nand four unusually large bed rooms.\nServant\u2019s room and bath in basement.\nadd greatly to its comfort. It is do\ntached and of all-brick construction\n6921 Fairfax Ro.d, $23,500\nEdgemoor, Md. 7\nTerm* may be arranged.\nTo reach, the property, dr/re north on Wis\nconsin Ace. to Bethe.sda Bank, turn left onto\nEdgemoor Lane and then .to Fairfax Road.\nFidelity Mortgage Investment Company\n507 11th Street N.W.\nNational 2431\n\nChevy Chase Corner\n*14,500\nFour Large Bed Rooms \u2014Detached Garage\u2014L#t 65\\120\nA very imposing corner home in a setting of fine shrubs,\nhedges and trees. Large reception hall and living room with\nopen fireplace; model kitchen with furnished breakfast nook; four\nbed rooms and sleeping porch; full width covered front porch;\nmaid's room, outside pantry, hot-water heat, hardwood floors, etc.\n5501 Nevada Avenue\n(Corner of Livingston)\nDrive right from Conn. Ave. on Livingston\nStreet two blocks to home and our sign,\nOPEN AIL DAY SUNDAY\n3. \u00a9ouglass Co.\nRealtors\n1621 K St. N.W. Metro. 5678\n\n3721 Porter St. N.W.\nNEW DETACHED RED BRICK\nFour beautiful bed rooms, two bright baths, Oil Tex walls,\nbig living and dining rooms, complete kitchen, concrete and brick\nsemi-private living porch, big breakfast porch, service porch,\nsleeping porch, abundance of wardrobe and storage closets, big\nattic with plenty windows. The equipment is complete, including\nelectric refrigerator, and the entire property is screened.\nThere is a two-car garage to match \u2014yet the price of this\nbeautiful home is only $19,750.\nOPEN AND LIGHTED DAILY\nTower Mctrop.\nbi.i@.\nThis attractive new home in Golf Club\nManor, containing 12 rooms, 4 baths, 2-car\ngarage, all modern improvements; near\nCountry Club and proposed George Washing\nton Memorial Parkway. Sale on easy terms,\nor exchange for smaller property.\nTo reach property, go out Lee Highway\npast Cherrydale to Glebe Road, turn rigjjt, go\nout Glebe Road past Country Club to Golf\nClub Manor. See our sign on right.\n_\nOpen Sunday\nW. S. Hoge, Jr.\n801 Shoreham Building\nDistrict 6563\nl\nMr. Bchmidt, a member of the associa\ntion\u2019s board of directors, will tell what\nthe realtor specializing in the mortgage\nand finance field must do to operate his\nbusiness with assurance of safety and\nprotection under present-day conditions.\nMortgage conditions throughout the\ncountry and the real estate loan meth\nods which must be applied for success\nful business during the coming year will\nbe explained by R. Graeme Smith of\nthe Connecticut General Life Insurance\nCo., Hartford Conn., who will address\nthe division on \"Problems of the Mort\ngage Banker in 1930 and Suggested So\nlutions.\nDetermining the cost of a new proj\nect and the best procedure in handling\nthese costs will be discussed by Victor\nGoggin, New York City, of Goggin\nRipley. Sydney Middleton. Chicago,\nwill tell what to do and what not to do\nin managing a mortgage business in his\ntalk on \"Policy Dangers in the Opera\ntion of a Mortgage Loan Bond Busi\nness.\u201d Mr. Middleton is vice chairman\nof the executive committee of the mort\ngage and finance division.\n\nA new synthetic resin withstands\n1 hammer blows and yet bends easily\nwh~n made up into thin sheets.\nREAL' ESTATE.\nSKYSCRAPER MEN OPEN\nBILOXI MEETING JUNE 9\nStudy of Operating and Rental\nProblems of Great Buildings\nWill Feature Convention.\nBy land, by sea and by air, the sky- j\nscraper men of America will begin their\njourney next week to Biloxi. Miss., to\nattend the twenty-third annual conven\ntion of the National Association of j\nBuilding Owners and Managers, which\nopens June 9.\nIn going to Biloxi, the skyscraper\nmen will be holding their annual con\nvention below the Mason and Dixon\nline for the first time in 15 years. The j\ndecision, to go South this year, it was\nexplained by Paul Robertson of Indian\nChevy Ch ase\nNo. 113 West Th ornapple Street\n$14,750\nS Located just west of Connecticut Avenue, In a setting\nof beautiful shade trees, this attractive Dutch Colonial\nhome represents a most appealing value.\nSeven rooms (four bed rooms) and tiled bath with\nshower. Large side porch; attic; built-in garage.\nEverything in perfect condition. VACANT.\nNo. 22 West Irving Street\n$15,950\nIn OLD CHEVY CHASE, one short block northwest\nI of Chevy Chase Circle, in a setting of towering shade\ntrees. PRICED TO SELL, you will find this attractive\nCENTER-HALL, 4-BED-ROOM home. Thoroughly MOD\nERN AND IN PERFECT CONDITION. Large screened\nsleeping porch; 2-CAR GARAGE; floored attic. Large\nlot. VACANT.\nI\nNo. 3235 Quesada Street\n$10,950\nNew' Dutch Colonial home facing south-\u20146 rooms and\n2 TILED BATHS; 2-CAR GARAGE,\ni This property represents as much value as we have\nseen in a long time. A visit of inspection will well repay\nyou.\nTo Reach: Goina out Conn. Are., turn from Chevy Chare\nCircle on Western Are., one short square to Quesada, over\nQuesada 3 squares to property.\nOPEN ALL DAY SUNDAY\nEdw. H. Jones fe? Co., Inc.\nChevy Chase Properties\n5520 Conn. Ave. Cleve. 2300\ni\n4613 l)c Russy Parkway, C. C., Md.\nBeautiful New Stone Home\nSeven Rooms\u2014Two Tile Baths\nWeather Stripped\u2014Screened\nTwo Open Fireplaces\nBilliard Room\n2-Car Garage\nl ot 65' front\u2014opposite Chevy Chase Club\nOwing to conditions owner is unable to\noccupy and will sell on good terms for only\n$15,500\nOpen From Ten to Dark Sunday\nDrive out Wise. Ave. to De Russy Parkway\nand turn left to the house\n[Shannon&luchS]\n1435 K Nat. 2345\ni\nMg jUBj all\nNe w Detached Homes in\nCHEVY CHASE\nOffered at the Surprisingly Low Price of\n$10,950\nThese houses are real 2-story-and-atlic homes with 6 rooms and\ntiled bath with built-in equipment; large porches, including full width\nsleeping porch; open fireplace, automatic heater, garage.\nPAVED STREET\u2014LARGE LOT\n6504-6 FULTON STREET\n(JHEVY CHASE, MD.\nTO Drive out Conn. Ave. to Taylor St., turn right two squares.\nOPEN SUNDAY ALL DAY\nJ company INC.\n1418 Eye St. N.W. Natl. 5904\napolii, president of the association, was\nmade in recognition of the great de\nvelopment that has taken place in the\nbusiness 'districts of Southern cities.\nThe convention will devote itself to\na concentrated study of operating and\nj rental problems of the Nation's greet\nbuildings. Exhibits of new operating\nI devices and rental campaigns have\nj arranged for in conjunction with the\nconvention.\nThe program includes addresses by\nseveral distinguished speakers, among\nthem Sidney W. Setters, executive vice\npresident of the Canal Bank and Trust\nCo. of New Orleans, who will speak on\n\"The Business Outlook,\" and Dr.\nMarion Luther Brittain, president of\nthe Georgia Institute of Technology of\nAtlanta. Ga\u201e who will speak on \"The\nYoung Man in Business.\u201d\nTourists visiting Czechoslovakia last\n1 year totaled 361.745.\nB-5","height":"25536","width":"19884"}}
